  "why": "The paper does not demonstrate or evaluate cross-model transferability. DeepTest is presented and evaluated as a white/gray-box testing approach applied to individual DNNs (it tests three different Udacity models separately) and the authors explicitly contrast their method with differential testing across multiple DNNs. The paper contains no design choices that aim to discover transferable failures (e.g., using a surrogate model to craft inputs) nor any experiments that reuse fault-inducing inputs discovered on one model to test others.",
  "evidence": "Page 304, Introduction / Contributions: \"We implement the proposed techniques in DeepTest, to the best of our knowledge, the first systematic and automated testing tool for DNN-driven autonomous vehicles. We use DeepTest to systematically test three top performing DNN models from the Udacity driving challenge.\" (Introduction / Key contributions) \n\nPage 312, Related Work: \"Pei et al. [70] proposed DeepXplore, a whitebox differential testing algorithm for systematically finding inputs that can trigger inconsistencies between multiple DNNs. ... By contrast, our graybox methods use neuron coverage for guided test generation in a single DNN and leverage metamorphic relations to identify erroneous behaviors without requiring multiple DNNs.\" (Section 7, Related Work)\n\nNo section of the paper proposes or reports experiments that (a) craft fault-inducing inputs on one model and then (b) reuse those inputs to evaluate other, independently trained target models (i.e., no cross-model reuse/transferability experiments are described). (See overall experimental Sections 4–5: tests and bug counts are reported per-model but no cross-model transfer analysis is performed.)"
